BEGIN_PGML Simplify [`24\div(15\div 3+1)+2\text{.}`]
[_]{6}{10}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION With the expression [`24\div(15\div 3+1) +2\text{,}`] we'll simplify what's inside the parentheses according to the order of operations, and then take [`24`] divided by that expression as our last step:
[```\newcommand{\highlight}[1]{\mathchoice{\colorbox{lightsapphire}{$\displaystyle #1$}}{\colorbox{lightsapphire}{$\textstyle #1$}}{\colorbox{lightsapphire}{$\scriptstyle #1$}}{\colorbox{lightsapphire}{$\scriptscriptstyle #1$}}}\newcommand{\nextoperation}[1]{\mathord{\boxed{#1}}}\newcommand{\amp}{&} \begin{aligned} \amp 24\div(15\div 3+1)+2 \amp\amp\nextoperation{15\div 3}\\ \amp=24\div(5+1)+2 \amp\amp\nextoperation{5+1}\\ \amp=24\div \highlight{6}+2\amp\amp\nextoperation{24\div 6}\\ \amp=\highlight{4}+2\\ \amp=\highlight{6} \end{aligned} ```]
END_PGML_SOLUTION
